{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564765"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:18:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:18:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17140"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17140"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.3,0.07,0.49,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9830"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92054"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9830"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17140"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75475"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2047"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3814"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23010"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31432"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92054"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of increasing fatigue and shortness of breath on exertion. She has no abdominal pain, change in bowel habits, or visible blood in her stool. Her medical history includes hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include amlodipine and paracetamol. She does not smoke and drinks two glasses of wine a week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale but well. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 128/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. Blood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 82 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean cell volume 76 fL (80-96)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFerritin 8 \u00b5g/L (30-200)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIron 4 \u00b5mol/L (10-30).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Iron studies","Faecal occult blood test","Upper endoscopy","Colonoscopy","CT abdomen"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptomatic iron deficiency anaemia, which is a common presentation of right-sided colon cancer. The ascending colon has a large luminal diameter, and tumours can grow quite large before causing obstruction. These tumours often present with iron deficiency anaemia due to chronic, occult blood loss rather than obvious bleeding or change in bowel habits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation as it allows direct visualisation of the colonic mucosa and enables tissue biopsy if a lesion is found. It is the gold standard investigation for suspected colorectal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFaecal occult blood testing\u003C/strong\u003E is used as a screening tool in asymptomatic individuals. In a patient with established iron deficiency anaemia, proceeding directly to colonoscopy is more appropriate as a negative faecal occult blood test would not obviate the need for endoscopic evaluation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron studies\u003C/strong\u003E would not add any additional useful information as we already have clear evidence of iron deficiency. Further investigation of the cause is required rather than confirming the deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not the initial investigation of choice. While CT staging will be required if cancer is found, colonoscopy provides better mucosal detail and the ability to take biopsies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUpper endoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered as part of the workup for iron deficiency anaemia, particularly in patients with upper gastrointestinal symptoms. However, given the age and presentation, colonoscopy should be performed first as colorectal cancer is more likely. In reality, this patient is likely to have a colonoscopy and upper endoscopy both done at the same time - even though colonoscopy is the most critical examination to perform.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Right-sided colon cancers typically present with iron deficiency anaemia due to chronic occult blood loss.","Colonoscopy is the gold standard investigation for suspected colorectal cancer.","CT staging of the chest, abdomen and pelvis is essential in newly diagnosed colorectal cancer."],"references":["Eng C, Yoshino T, Ru\u00edz-Garc\u00eda E, Mostafa N, Cann CG, O\u2019Brian B, et al. Colorectal cancer. The Lancet. 2024 Jul 20;404(10449):294\u2013310. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(24)00360-X/abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75475"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17140"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75475","links":